column6: State = Virginia&&&&United States Marine Corps&&&&"$50&&&&000-$59&&&&999"&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&"The career services was completely clueless when it came to handling individuals with prior military service. I visited with them several times between graduating in May and obtaining my acceptance to officer candidate school. They had zero influence when it came to helping me find a job. I think this was primarily due to the novice councilors I had and the fact that they did not understand how to help me find a career. Over and over my r̩sum̩ was rejected and I was forced to translate my military experience into other terms that employers could relate. The problem with this was that I was not interested in working for employers who did not understand what my experience meant. A one page r̩sum̩ was insufficient for many of the positions and careers I was applying for. To be forced to create such a r̩sum̩ undermined my abilities and experience and was not acceptable to many of the career fields I was applying for. I don't feel like my counselors really were listening to me and helping me to the best of their ability. I felt like just another number and that they treated me like any other student&&&& green to the world. I also don't think they knew how to help someone like me who had many years of expereince in very technical military related fields. Fortunately&&&& I was selected into the program i applied for long before graduation. Lastly&&&& it is important to note that many of the companies out there are using high tech r̩sum̩ filtering systems. It is not a secret but it might as well be because this important factor was left out of our counseling sessions. Why are we not striving to beat this system? The biggest thing the university of Texas could change&&&& for me and others like me&&&& would be to have a career counselor who primarily works with veterans and knows what companies hire veterans locally&&&& nationally&&&& and internationally. They should be able to understand the differences between military branches and job fields&&&& not just try to dumb down my terminology. There should never be someone like myself who has served in an exemplary fashion&&&& strengthened local communities&&&& received a bachelors&&&& and remainsed unemployed for 7 months while actively looking for jobs that combined my military and college backgrounds. Hopefully&&&& the SVA has already realized this and is working to incorporate te much needed changes to LACS."\r

This needs to be a consistent conversation throughout the undergraduate experience and it has to start with advisors followed by the career center. column6: Talking about what you have to offer = Low Confidence&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&"Mandatory internship experience. Make companies' networking events better-known. Stress the importance of these networking/recruiting events from the first semester at UT and the opportunities available to us&&&& it's just up to us to take advantage of them. Make it well-known that simply graduating from UT does not guarantee better job placement compared to graduates from other schools of less quality. Perhaps require at least one career advising session per semester starting sophomore year. Remind us that we will likely be working with people who have had a far less (or greater) educational experience than us&&&& and they might not understand what we think we do. We won't be surrounded by the smartest ten percent of people forever&&&& and it's very frustating trying to deal with these people in a productive work environment.UT was by far the best four years of my life&&&& and I'm still coping with the let-downs that the real world is bringing by comparison. I would love nothing more than to go back for another four years&&&& but I have to start paying my own bills some time sooner rather than later."\r

This perspective forced me to work even harder to get what I wanted.  After applying for well over 50 jobs and having well over 30 interviews with multiple rounds and travel&&&& I received one offer&&&& but not without blood&&&& sweat&&&& tears&&&& stress&&&& and a healthy dose of reality guiding me along my way. column6: State = Ohio&&&&JP Morgan Chase&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&"As an economics major that graduated in 2012. I can confidently say that recruiting is LACKING for our major. We have many skills and qualifications that companies value. Our classes are heavily quantitative and require intense dedication and understanding of the subject matter. I think that there should be separate recruiting for ECO majors&&&& or they should get some privy into business school recruits. I know for a fact (after returning to UT and recruiting at the Mccombs career fair for my company) that there are very unique skills that ECO majors have&&&& and the students will be visible. There should be more help on resume building in the ECO school and advisors should be taking a much more active role in this. I was not satisfied with the over simplification of the LACS. There should be some specialization implemented
column7: geared towards individual majors and career trajectories. Please reach out to me if you would like further input. I have a great interest in this topic."\r

column6: State = Texas&&&&Austin Travis County Integral Care&&&&"$20&&&&000-$29&&&&999"&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&&"I would have liked to have known how difficult it is to get a job. I applied to over 65 jobs and received 2 phone calls and 1 interview. The main reason I landed the interview was because a close friend of mine was good friends with the boss who was hiring. I applied for this job twice. The first time they did not notice my application. The second time&&&& after my friend recommended me&&&& I received a phone call&&&& had an interview and was hired later that day. I am very thankful for the job that I have now&&&& and I know that I received a great education from UT Austin&&&& however&&&& I wish I could have been more mentally prepared for the job search. I was under the impression that college graduates actually get hired. But what is more important is networking. Friends get you interviews&&&& not your credentials. I wish I had either taken the time to make more friends and acquaintances in my field or simply mentally prepared myself for constant disappointment and degradation."\r
